'''Joseph McGeachy Thomson''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|FRSE}} (6 May 1948 – 12 May 2018<ref>[http://www.legacy.com/obituaries/thetimes-uk/obituary.aspx?n=joseph-thomson-joe&pid=189020354 Professor Joseph "Joe" Thomson]</ref>) was a Scottish lawyer and academic. He was Regius Professor of Law at the University of Glasgow and a member of the [[Scottish Law Commission]].

==Early life==
Thomson was born in Campbeltown and attended the independent [[Keil School]] in Dumbarton. He then studied at the [[University of Edinburgh]], where he graduated LLB in 1970<ref name="ugstory">{{cite web|title=Joe Thomson|url=http://www.universitystory.gla.ac.uk/biography/?id=WH1749&type=P|publisher=[[University of Glasgow]]|accessdate=1 March 2010}}</ref> and was awarded the Lord President Cooper Memorial Prize as the outstanding LLB honours graduate.<ref name=cooper>{{cite web|title=Lord President Cooper Memorial Prize Scholarship|url=http://www.law.ed.ac.uk/prizes/lordpresidentcooper.aspx|accessdate=13 April 2012}}</ref>

==Career==
Following his graduation, Thomson was appointed lecturer at the [[University of Birmingham]], moving in 1974 to [[King's College London]].<ref name="ugstory"/> In 1984, he became Professor of Law at the [[University of Strathclyde]], and in 1991 was appointed to the [[Regius Chair of Law, Glasgow|Regius Chair in Law]] at the [[University of Glasgow School of Law|School of Law]] of the [[University of Glasgow]].<ref name="abdn">{{cite web|title=Joe Thomson|url=http://www.abdn.ac.uk/causation/uploads/files/Joseph%20Thomson.pdf|publisher=[[University of Aberdeen]]|accessdate=1 March 2010}}</ref> He was elected a fellow of the [[Royal Society of Edinburgh]] in 1996,<ref name=debretts>{{cite web|title=Prof Joseph Thomson, FRSE|url=http://www.debretts.co.uk/people/biographies/browse/t/12970/Joseph%20McGeachy+THOMSON.aspx|accessdate=12 April 2012}}</ref> and was President of the Society of Public Teachers of Law (now the [[The Society of Legal Scholars|Society of Legal Scholars]]) in 2000-2001.<ref>{{cite book|last=Society of Legal Scholars|title=Directory of Members, 2011/12|year=2012|publisher=Wiley-Blackwell|pages=ix}}</ref> He was appointed to a five-year term on the [[Scottish Law Commission]] in 2000, and received a further four-year term in 2005, at which point he resigned from the Glasgow Chair. He was formerly editor of the ''Juridical Review'',<ref name="debretts" /> the oldest Scottish legal journal.

