A '''shujra''' or '''shujrah''' is a detailed village map that is used for legal (land ownership) and administrative purposes in [[India]] and [[Pakistan]]. A ''shujra'' maps out the village lands into land parcels and gives each parcel a unique number.<ref name="ref69huvac">{{Citation | title=The West Pakistan land revenue act, 1967, and West Pakistan land revenue rules, 1968: with provincial amendments | author=Muhammad Iqbal Khan Mokal, West Pakistan | publisher=Law Publishing Co., 1973 | isbn= | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UB09AAAAYAAJ | quote=''... The village map showing the position and boundaries of every field is known as Shujra Kishtwar ...''}}</ref><ref name="ref68vapuj">{{Citation | title=Report of the National Commission on Agriculture, 1976: Agrarian reforms | author=National Commission on Agriculture | publisher=Ministry of Agriculture and Irrigation, Government of India, 1977 | isbn= | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1ulHAAAAYAAJ | quote=''... contents of record of rights in Punjab, Haryana, Himachal Pradesh and Union Territory of Delhi are as below: (i) a preliminary proceeding; (ii) a field map (Shujra Kishtwar); (iii) an index of field numbers ...''}}</ref> The ''[[village accountant|patwari]]'' (or village accountant) maintains a record for each one of these parcels in documents called ''[[khasra]]s''.<ref name="ref52micaq">{{Citation | title=The Land Systems of British India: Being a Manual of the Land-tenures and of the Systems of Land-revenue Administration Prevalent in the Several Provinces | author=Baden Henry Baden-Powell | publisher=Clarendon Press, 1892 | isbn= | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6vVKAAAAYAAJ | quote=''...The Shujra or village map ... The khasra, or index register to the map. It is a list showing, by numbers, all the fields and their areas, measurement, who owns and what cultivators he employs, what crops, what sort of soil, what trees are on the land ...''}}</ref><ref name="ref09fulez">{{Citation | title=The Central Administration of the East India Company 1773-1834 | author=Bankey Bihari Misra | publisher=Manchester University Press, 1959 | isbn= | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FqHnAAAAIAAJ | quote=''... The preparation of a detailed field map called Shujra in which the fields were numbered. The patwari was then to register all the field numbers in a corresponding field book called khasra which also contained the name of the proprietor ...''}}</ref>
'''Aks-Shajra''' is the copy of the map.
